Twenty -five towns belonged to the conventus of Cibyra, and its commercial transactions were probably large. As to the limits of Bithynia after it became a Roman province, see Dict. Geog. It included a great part of Pontus, and so comprised nearly the whole sea-coast of Asia Minor on the Euxine. Its trade therefore must have been very great, since the Halys alone must have brought down vast quantities of merchandize, and there were other navigable rivers, as the Lycus, Iris, Parthenius, Sangarius, communioeting with the interior. It had also convenient harbours on the Propontis, and was only separated from Europe by the narrow Thracian Bosporus. Its mountains pro- duced valuable minerals and precious stones and marblae of different kinds.
